d the German comedic tradition, and examine the relation of these genres to political, religious, and philosophical issues. In addition, the volume includes several essays on the role tragedy and comedy play in Hegel's philosophy of history. This book will not only be valuable to those who wish for a general overview of Hegel's treatment of tragedy and comedy but also to those who want to understand how his treatment of these genres is connected to the rest of his thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aGreek drama (Comedy)xHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aGreek drama (Comedy)--History and criticism--Theory, etc. 0aGreek drama (Tragedy)xHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aGreek drama (Tragedy)--History and criticism--Theory, etc. 0aHegel, Georg Wilhelm Friedrich, 1770-1831. 4aLiterature : Drama. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aAlznauer, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarba-Kay, Antón, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChurch, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonougho, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalkenstern, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinn, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFurlotte, Wes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeneghan, Fiacha D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuft, Eric v. d., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpeight, C. Allen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWake, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel